👉Paraphenylenediamine (PPD) is found in 70% of hair dyes and it has been reported that 11.5% Indians are sensitive to PPD. And yes !! your beloved “kali mehendi” is actually a dye only!!

⚠️ It might sound organic but pure henna in itself will give a dark red hue at the max, but the commercially available black mehendi that gives black color, actually contains paraphenylenediamine (PPD). So if you are allergic to hair dyes, you will react to that as well.

Here are the Do’s and Don’t of hair coloring:

🌟 Always perform a patch test before using a new hair color
- Apply a small amount behind your ear, keep for 20-25min (or the time you usually keep your hair dye), wash off and observe for 24-48 hours for any reaction.
- Allergic reaction may be immediate or may even occur up to 48 hours
- To minimise reaction choose a PPD free dye, which is the most common irritant in hair dyes

🌟 Choose a hair color within 2-3 shades of your natural hair color

🌟 If you are planning to get a chemical treatment (keratin, smoothening, hair Botox) along with hair colouring, go for the chemical treatment first, wait for at least 2 weeks 17 and then color your hair.
- If done together may lead to severe hair damage

PPD free options: ( but perform a patch test before using them as well)
1. Altris HD hair hue therapy
2. Vegetal Bio color
3. Cuticolor Hair colouring cream
4. ⁠Indus Valley Gel hair color
5. ⁠Kama Ayurvedic Organic hair color
